You are executing the 03-Descriptive-Modeling skill. This skill MUST generate Section 2.0 (Descriptive Modeling) of the SRS by reading `../project_context/tech_stack.md`, `features.md`, and `quality_standards.md`, then updating `../output/SRS_Draft.md` with the required subsections.

1. Determine the parent root (`../`) and confirm the existence of the three context files. Log each file read with its relative path.
2. Extract infrastructure keywords (Ubuntu, Debian, OCI, MySQL, PostgreSQL, HP Z440, NVMe, RAM, TPM) from `tech_stack.md` to describe system interfaces, hardware interfaces, and memory constraints. Reflect HP Z440 mentions as on-premise/workstation context.
3. Parse `features.md` to group features into logical Major Capability blocks (e.g., Verification & Traceability, Maintenance & Operations). Avoid adjectives; favor direct descriptions like "MySQL 8.0 instance optimized for concurrency."
4. Read `quality_standards.md` for constraints (ISO/IEC 25051, ISO/IEC 25010) and list assumptions/dependencies accordingly.
5. Compose Section 2.0 with the following subsections per IEEE 830 §5.2:
   - 2.1 Product Perspective (with all eight sub-items per IEEE 830 §5.2.1):
     - 2.1.1 System Interfaces (list each system interface with functionality and interface description)
     - 2.1.2 User Interfaces (logical characteristics, screen layouts, accessibility constraints)
     - 2.1.3 Hardware Interfaces (logical characteristics, ports, protocols, device support)
     - 2.1.4 Software Interfaces (Name, Version, Source for each dependency; interface purpose and message format)
     - 2.1.5 Communications Interfaces (network protocols, local network requirements)
     - 2.1.6 Memory Constraints (primary and secondary memory characteristics and limits)
     - 2.1.7 Operations (normal/special operations, interactive/unattended periods, backup and recovery)
     - 2.1.8 Site Adaptation Requirements (site-specific data, initialization sequences, mission-related modifications)
     - System Block Diagram description mentioning actual infrastructure components
   - 2.2 Product Functions (major capability buckets with logical relationships)
   - 2.3 User Characteristics (education, experience, technical expertise of intended user groups)
   - 2.4 Constraints (regulatory, hardware, interface, parallel operation, audit, control, language, protocol, reliability, criticality, safety/security — reference ISO/IEC 25051)
   - 2.5 Assumptions and Dependencies (factors affecting requirements that are not design constraints)
   - 2.6 Apportioning of Requirements (IEEE 830 §5.2.6 — list requirements deferred to future versions; if none exist, state: "No requirements are apportioned to future versions at this time.")
6. Reference the IEEE 830 compliance checklist at `../ieee-830-compliance-checklist.md` (IDs IEEE830-5.2.1 through IEEE830-5.2.6) to verify all required subsections are present before writing output.
7. Replace any existing Section 2.0 block in `SRS_Draft.md` with the newly constructed section. Keep the remainder of the document intact.
8. Log each major action (files read, features grouped, section written) using explicit relative paths.
9. Maintain technical tone, use SHALL when prescribing behavior, and ensure tables/bullet lists render cleanly in Markdown. Mention ISO/IEC 25051 and local environmental factors (power/internet stability in Uganda) within constraints.
